# Django for professionals steps: 
# run: sudo docker run hello-world then sudo docker info (make sure its running)
#  Create a directory to create a venv and install django in 
# run:  python3 -m venv .djangovenv (or whatever venv name you want)
# source .djangovenv/bin/activate
# then in the venv run: python -m pip install django 
# to up date it python -m pip install --upgrade pip
# start the project run(don't forget the dot, if you do rm -r django_project): django-admin startproject django_project .
#  (the book says to do this) python manage.py migrate
# python manage.py runserver
# run: python manage.py startapp <app name> (ie. python manage.py startapp pages)
# To start app(install new tracker directory and its files): python manage.py startapp tracker
    # In django_project/settings.py put it under INSTALLED_APPS 
# not done yet#    # Set the homepage URL route (pg 22)- resume from there to requirements.txt(pg 24)

# make a requirements.txt : pip freeze > requirements.txt
# Deactivate your venv via command: deactivate (now you will set up docker)
# Create a Dockerfile in project-level directory(where manage.py is)(pg 26)
# Create a .dockerignore file
# Run sudo docker build . 
# Create docker-compose.yml (pg 29)
# Run sudo docker compose up 
# Run docker compose down
# Create a .gitignore file
# Run git init
# Run git status
# Run git add . 
# Run git commit -m <message>
# Run git push -u origin main